T*
(Problem definition) Tj
T*
(Road-network-constrained trajectory recovery studies how to reconstruct a dense trajectory,) Tj
T*
(a route-segment sequence, or a complete path from sparse and partially missing observations) Tj
T*
(while preserving explicit topological feasibility on the road network. Unlike conventional) Tj
T*
(map matching, the task is not limited to aligning observed points to candidate roads; it) Tj
T*
(must also infer latent locations, connecting segments, and path legality over the missing) Tj
T*
(intervals under a unified model. The problem is therefore a coupled estimation task over) Tj
T*
(topology, spatiotemporal dependence, and uncertainty induced by low sampling rates, long) Tj
T*
(missing spans, and irregular sampling intervals. As a result, the literature has converged) Tj
T*
(on map-constrained sparse-GPS recovery as the core benchmark setting, while camera-based) Tj
T*
(recovery, multimodal recovery, and generative completion extend the task boundary rather) Tj
T*
(than replace its main formulation. \(Trace to the evidence map for representative paper ids) Tj
T*
(before replacing these notes with `\\cite{...}` commands in the final ACM manuscript.\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Method evolution) Tj
T*
(The methodological line first grew from constrained path inference and sequence restoration,) Tj
T*
(where sparse observations were completed by searching road-feasible transitions and learning) Tj
T*
(map-aware recovery under strong structural priors. It then moved toward graph-enhanced and) Tj
T*
(transformer-style recovery, where richer spatial representations, longer-range road) Tj
T*
(dependencies, and interval-aware temporal modeling improved performance beyond local) Tj
T*
(transition heuristics. More recent work broadens the design space again by incorporating) Tj
T*
(pretrained models, streaming inference, multimodal cues, and generative mechanisms to better) Tj
T*
(handle longer missing spans, irregular intervals, and higher uncertainty. Across these) Tj
T*
(shifts, however, sparse-GPS road-network reconstruction remains the dominant evaluation) Tj
T*
(anchor, so newer paradigms are still judged by how well they preserve or extend this core) Tj
T*
(recovery setting. \(Insert final citations using the paper ids listed in) Tj
T*
(`docs/0402/20260402_KDD??_???????_v2_????.md`.\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Limitations of prior work) Tj
T*
(Despite rapid progress, prior studies still optimize point-wise reconstruction more directly) Tj
T*
(than route validity or segment-level fidelity, so gains on MAE- or RMSE-style metrics do not) Tj
T*
(necessarily imply stronger path recovery quality. A second limitation is that road-network) Tj
T*
(knowledge remains unevenly incorporated: weaker methods underuse structural priors, whereas) Tj
T*
(stronger graph or semantic designs often introduce heavier assumptions, curated inputs, or) Tj
T*
(higher transfer cost across cities and sensing regimes. Generalization evidence is also) Tj
T*
(thinner than in-distribution accuracy evidence, especially under irregular intervals,) Tj
T*
(observation shift, and cross-domain deployment. Finally, foundation-model and generative) Tj
T*
(directions enlarge the modeling space, but they still leave unresolved how to maintain) Tj
T*
(topology consistency, data efficiency, and operational stability under strict road) Tj
T*
(constraints. \(Replace this trace note with KDD-style citations once the bibliography mirror) Tj
T*
(is restored.\)) Tj
T*
